english:
  title: A Letter to Prime Minister Choe
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I, Lee [name], National University Chancellor, Court Attendant in the Imperial Academy, and Drafter of Edicts, humbly submit this letter to Your Excellency, the Prime Minister.

    I am by nature worthless and mediocre, yet through your gracious recognition, I have been undeservedly elevated. Within mere years of entering service, my rank has already risen to the third grade, and I have taken on the duties of both Academic and Edict Drafter without exception. Even the ancients who found true patrons and received the favor of great men could not compare to the honor you have bestowed upon me. Yet your generosity extends beyond mere advancement—you have also counseled me to drink sparingly, understanding that my small capacity for wine leads easily to madness when exceeded. Such wisdom surpasses even the precepts of all Buddhas and Bodhisattvas, or the teachings of parents to their children. I should have guarded this counsel steadfastly, never allowing even a whisper of my transgression to reach your ears. And yet, I have failed.

    At the Eight Gates banquet, His Majesty mistakenly believed me a capable drinker and personally filled my cup repeatedly with earnest insistence. I hesitated at first, hoping to escape intoxication, but seeing the royal countenance, I dared not refuse and forced myself to drink deeply. Thus I fell into such confusion that I lost all sense. This was not my true intention, but rather the result of my greedy heart accepting imperial favor without knowing the limits of my vessel. Who else can I blame?

    Because of this, I could not attend the subsequent court gathering in the proper manner. The officials spread rumors that reached His Majesty's ears and even touched upon your name. Though I would accept ten thousand deaths as punishment, I must rely on your protection and generosity. You have pardoned me entirely—a kindness vast as heaven and earth, impossible to repay in a single lifetime.

    Considering my transgressions: First, I failed in the duties of a court attendant. Second, I betrayed your trust in me. Third, I ignored your counsel. My stains run so deep that even great rivers cannot wash them clean. Though I am fortunate to receive your clemency, what face have I to stand again in court?

    I humbly beseech you to dismiss me from office at this very moment, allowing me to retire to the countryside—a great mercy indeed. Should you not do so, and instead show magnanimous forgiveness by restoring me to court, I ask only that my rank be reduced and I be moved away from the intimate circle near His Majesty. This too would be a profound gift.

    This is no hollow flattery, but the sincere cry of my heart. I await your merciful judgment.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Eight Gates banquet (八關會) was a major court celebration held during the Goryeo period.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three-character position' refers to high court ranks, whose titles consisted of three Chinese characters.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Gyubo (1168-1241) was a prominent Goryeo scholar-official and writer, and this letter exemplifies the formal style of official correspondence in medieval Korea.
